# Jekyll Best Practices and Coding Standards

## Project Structure
Follow the standard Jekyll directory structure:
```
.
├── _config.yml          # Site configuration
├── _data/               # Data files (YAML, JSON, CSV)
├── _drafts/             # Unpublished posts
├── _includes/           # Reusable components
├── _layouts/            # Page templates
├── _posts/              # Blog posts (YYYY-MM-DD-title.md)
├── _sass/               # Sass partials
├── _site/               # Generated site (ignored by git)
├── assets/              # CSS, JS, images
├── _pages/              # Static pages
├── index.html           # Homepage
├── Gemfile              # Ruby dependencies
├── .gitignore           # Git ignore rules
└── README.md            # Project documentation
```

## Core Principles
- **Static First**: Jekyll transforms Markdown, Liquid, HTML & CSS into static sites
- **Content-Driven**: Focus on content, not complex databases or updates
- **Blog-Aware**: Built-in support for permalinks, categories, pages, posts, and layouts
- **GitHub Pages Ready**: Optimized for free hosting on GitHub Pages

## File Naming Conventions
- **Posts**: `YYYY-MM-DD-title.md` in `_posts/` directory
- **Pages**: `title.md` or `title/index.md` for clean URLs
- **Drafts**: `title.md` in `_drafts/` directory
- **Data Files**: `.yml`, `.yaml`, `.json`, or `.csv` in `_data/`
- **Includes**: `_component-name.html` in `_includes/`
- **Layouts**: `layout-name.html` in `_layouts/`

## Front Matter Standards
Always include proper front matter in posts and pages:
```yaml
---
layout: post
title: "Post Title"
date: 2024-01-01 12:00:00 -0000
categories: [category1, category2]
tags: [tag1, tag2]
author: Author Name
---
```

## Liquid Template Best Practices
- Use `{{ content }}` for page content
- Use `{{ site.title }}` for site-wide variables
- Use `{% for post in site.posts %}` for post loops
- Use `{% include component.html %}` for reusable components
- Use `{% assign variable = value %}` for variable assignment

## Asset Management
- Place CSS in `assets/css/` or `_sass/`
- Place JavaScript in `assets/js/`
- Place images in `assets/images/`
- Use `{{ site.baseurl }}{{ '/assets/image.jpg' | relative_url }}` for asset URLs
- Optimize images before adding to repository

## Configuration (_config.yml)
Essential configuration settings:
```yaml
title: "Site Title"
description: "Site description"
baseurl: "" # for GitHub Pages: "/repository-name"
url: "https://username.github.io" # or custom domain

# Build settings
markdown: kramdown
highlighter: rouge
theme: minima # or custom theme

# Collections
collections:
  - name: "collection-name"
    output: true

# Defaults
defaults:
  - scope:
      path: ""
      type: "posts"
    values:
      layout: "post"
```

## GitHub Pages Integration
- Use `github-pages` gem in Gemfile
- Configure `baseurl` for repository-based sites
- Use `relative_url` filter for internal links
- Test locally with `bundle exec jekyll serve`
- Deploy automatically on push to main branch

## Performance Optimization
- Minimize external dependencies
- Use Jekyll's built-in Sass compilation
- Optimize images and use appropriate formats
- Leverage Jekyll's incremental builds
- Use `jekyll-sitemap` for SEO

## Security Best Practices
- Never commit sensitive data to repository
- Use environment variables for API keys
- Validate user input in forms
- Keep dependencies updated
- Use HTTPS for custom domains

## Development Workflow
1. Create feature branch
2. Make changes locally
3. Test with `bundle exec jekyll serve`
4. Commit and push changes
5. Create pull request
6. Merge to main for automatic deployment

## Common Patterns
- Use `{% raw %}{% endraw %}` to escape Liquid syntax
- Use `{% comment %}{% endcomment %}` for comments
- Use `{% unless condition %}{% endunless %}` for negative conditions
- Use `{% if condition %}{% elsif %}{% else %}{% endif %}` for conditionals

